{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:54:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:54:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17712"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72094"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10426"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57564"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10445"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24354"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72094"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESound waves travel through the external auditory canal and cause movement of structures in the middle ear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal sequence of sound transmission through the middle ear ossicles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tympanic membrane to incus to stapes to malleus","Tympanic membrane to stapes to malleus to incus","Tympanic membrane to malleus to incus to stapes","Tympanic membrane to malleus to stapes to incus","Tympanic membrane to incus to malleus to stapes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESound waves cause the tympanic membrane to vibrate, which then moves the \u003Cstrong\u003Emalleus\u003C/strong\u003E, followed by the \u003Cstrong\u003Eincus\u003C/strong\u003E, and finally the \u003Cstrong\u003Estapes\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the correct anatomical arrangement and functional sequence of the ossicles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect sequences can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe sequence of \u003Cstrong\u003Etympanic membrane to stapes to malleus to incus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the malleus is directly attached to the tympanic membrane and must be the first ossicle to move.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe sequence of \u003Cstrong\u003Etympanic membrane to incus to malleus to stapes\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the malleus must be the first ossicle to move as it attaches directly to the tympanic membrane.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe sequence of \u003Cstrong\u003Etympanic membrane to malleus to stapes to incus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the incus forms the bridge between the malleus and stapes and cannot be moved last.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe sequence of \u003Cstrong\u003Etympanic membrane to incus to stapes to malleus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because it describes an anatomically impossible arrangement of the ossicles.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ossicular chain functions as a lever system that amplifies force from the tympanic membrane to the oval window. This amplification, combined with the surface area difference between the tympanic membrane and oval window, allows efficient transfer of sound energy from air to the fluid-filled cochlea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ossicles amplify sound waves through a lever action mechanism and increase in force due to difference in tympanic membrane versus oval window surface area.","Sound waves cause the tympanic membrane to vibrate, which moves the malleus, incus, and stapes in sequence.","The stapes footplate creates pressure waves in the perilymph of the cochlea through the oval window."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57564"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17712"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57564"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:27:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:28:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10426"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72094"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving 